    <text>
        <body>
            <head>312. Memorandum From the Counselor of the Department of State (<persName
                    corresp="rectgy2hXleek4j6N">Kampelman</persName>) to Secretary of State
                    <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d312fn1">Source: Reagan Library,
                        <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName> Papers, June 1988
                    Meeting w/ President. Secret; Sensitive. Not for the System.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1988-06-10"
                        >June 10, 1988</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>WHETHER TO GO FOR A <gloss target="#t_START_1">START</gloss>
                    <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">TREATY</rs>
                </item>
            </list>
            <p>Our stated position—a correct one—following the <rs type="event"
                    corresp="recHp9uQv5w7SafI2">Summit</rs> is that we will continue our efforts to
                make progress on <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> and see how far we can get; we would like to conclude a <gloss
                    target="#t_START_1">START</gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">Treaty</rs> in this <rs
                    type="event" corresp="recrvfeHjk0YIZ1si">Administration</rs>; but we will not be
                rushed to decision by the calendar.</p>
            <p>It will come as no surprise to you that many in and out of Government have concluded
                that “the air is out of the souffle” and there is virtually no chance of concluding
                a <gloss target="#t_START_1">START</gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">Treaty</rs> this year.
                Some welcome this outcome as avoiding a “rush to decision” on difficult <gloss
                    target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> issues.</p>
            <p>I am concerned we not drift into a situation where drift alone makes a <rs
                    type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">Treaty</rs> impossible.
                We should make a conscious decision now whether to press for a <rs
                    type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">Treaty</rs> or
                concentrate instead on consolidating the maximum amount of agreement to pass on to
                the next Administration.</p>
            <p>A <gloss target="#t_START_1">START</gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">Treaty</rs> this year
                is, in my opinion, not achievable unless the Soviets agree at the final end game to
                put aside the two most difficult issues—<gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCMs</rs>
                </gloss> and <gloss target="#t_SDI_1">
                    <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">SDI</rs>
                </gloss>. This is quite possible, but even with this Soviet acquiescence, it is
                highly uncertain whether Washington can organize itself to make the extraordinary
                effort necessary to arrive at decisions on the range of other remaining difficult
                    <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> issues, such as <rs type="topic" corresp="recDqeb7aygg9Rdy8">suspect site
                    inspections</rs>, <rs type="topic" corresp="recInQ6JTYKBeryID">mobile</rs>
                <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic">verification</rs>, <gloss
                    target="#t_ALCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                </gloss>, <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs>, and a <rs
                    corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">throw-weight</rs> protocol.</p>
            <pb facs="1475" n="1448" xml:id="pg_1448"/>
            <p>The list of obstacles is daunting, but the Soviets may still want to conclude a
                    <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> agreement with the Reagan <rs type="event" corresp="recrvfeHjk0YIZ1si"
                    >administration</rs>. If we were within sight of agreement on all other <gloss
                    target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> issues, they just might settle for a declaration on <gloss
                    target="#t_SLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCMs</rs>
                </gloss> and a ban on <hi rendition="simple_italic">deployment</hi> of <gloss
                    target="#t_SDI_1">
                    <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">SDI</rs>
                </gloss> for a certain number of years. But even if the Soviets do not agree, we
                would have a package and could use it to our advantage when the issue of “blame” for
                no agreement is raised. I fully expect the Soviets to come in with their initiatives
                in a public way on July 12. (I expect to be in Geneva that first week.)</p>
            <p>Whatever slim chance there may be now for a <rs type="agreement-or-mandate"
                    corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">Treaty</rs> in 1988, the odds will decrease quickly
                with time. We should decide now, therefore, whether or not to go for it. We should
                also recognize that if we are to have a shot at it, a maximum effort from the top
                will be required. That will mean, among other things, forcing decisions out of a
                reluctant inter-agency bureaucracy. This will require the personal commitment and
                direction of the <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">President</persName> with
                those who would prefer to go slow, such as <gloss target="#t_JCS_1">
                    <orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah">JCS</orgName>
                </gloss>. The <gloss target="#t_JCS_1">
                    <orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah">JCS</orgName>
                </gloss> should understand that in a Dukakis Presidency, there is unlikely to be a
                2/3 <orgName corresp="recAXl1eLE0USmC6Z">Senate</orgName> ratification vote. We
                would then be left with no Soviet <rs type="topic" corresp="recHoFOsQcM4e5M4k">50%
                    reductions</rs> and unilateral US reductions by virtue of <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recJgxebpUYqWj25O">budget</rs> cuts.</p>
            <p>I recommend that in your next private meeting with <persName
                    corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">the President</persName>, you discuss <gloss
                    target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> prospects frankly. Whatever his decision, we can then execute it
                politically and organize ourselves accordingly.</p>
        </body>
